MULTIPLE DISEASES, GINGER, BLACK PEPPER, COFFEE - INDIA: (KARNATAKA, KERALA)
****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 26 Aug 2018 22:29 IST
Source: The Hindu [edited]
https://www.thehindu.com/business/post-rains-plantation-sector-tots-up-losses/article24786598.ece


Ginger farms in Kerala and Karnataka [were] submerged in floods starting June [2018]. Ginger rhizomes have since been affected by the soft rot disease. Heavy rains in ginger growing districts flooded the fields. They wiped out rhizomes on almost 5000 hectares [about 12 360 acres] in Karnataka and 2500 hectares [about 6180 acres] in Kerala, [the] South Indian Ginger Growers' Association [said].

"Torrential rains have washed off black pepper vines in many parts of the 2 states," [the] Indian Pepper and Spice Traders, Farmers, Producers and Planters Consortium said. "High moisture has triggered diseases like quick wilt and soft wilt." Pepper production may fall 40-50 per cent.

The Coffee Board has launched a comprehensive calamity survey to assess the loss in the sector, including crop loss, damage to plants, green berry dropping and black rot disease, due to the flood [the] Coffee Board (Extension) said. Coffee industry sources said 'Arabica' coffee production is likely to fall about 30 per cent and the Robusta variety by about 20 per cent in the country in 2018-19.

[Byline: EM Manoj]

